<header>
<h1>Pavitra Jha</h1>
<p class="sub">
Offensive security researcher focused on browser, Android, and Linux kernel security with emphasis on real-world exploitability and system-level vulnerability research.
</p>

<p class="sub">
16 years old. Security research since age 9. Work spans execution engines, kernel attack surfaces, sandbox boundaries, and privilege escalation paths in production systems.
</p>
</header>

<section>
<h2>Technical Capability</h2>

<div class="card">Browser Security: V8 internals, JIT pipelines, memory corruption primitives, exploitation techniques under modern mitigations</div>
<div class="card">Android Security: framework attack surfaces, Binder IPC, SELinux policy, kernel interaction paths</div>
<div class="card">Linux Kernel Security: driver flaws, race conditions, memory safety issues, upstream fixes analysis</div>
<div class="card">Sandbox & Mitigations: ASLR, KASLR, CFG, CFI, PAC, sandbox escape conditions</div>
<div class="card">Reverse Engineering: ARM64, x86, x64 across Windows, Linux, Android</div>
<div class="card">Fuzzing: structured fuzzing, crash triage, exploitability validation, harness design</div>
<div class="card">Source Audit: large-scale code review and architecture-level vulnerability discovery</div>

</section>

<section>
<h2>Research Approach</h2>
<ul>
<li>Exploitability-first reasoning model</li>
<li>Architecture-level vulnerability discovery</li>
<li>Logic + memory corruption hybrid exploitation thinking</li>
<li>Cross-boundary privilege escalation modeling</li>
<li>Systemic failure analysis over isolated bug hunting</li>
</ul>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Selected Public Record</h2>

<div class="card">
Linux Kernel Security Contributions<br>
Security-related kernel work involving driver-level issues, memory safety fixes, and upstream patch discussions across Linux subsystems.<br>
<a href="https://lore.kernel.org/all/?q=Pavitra+Jha">Linux Kernel Mailing List (LKML)</a>
</div>

<div class="card">
Philips Healthcare Security Vulnerability (Firmware ROP / Image Management System 15.1)<br>
Remote Code Execution (RCE) via a critical stack-based buffer overflow vulnerability in the processing component of Philips Image Management System 15.1 firmware. By overflowing the data buffer and utilizing a Return-Oriented Programming (ROP) chain, arbitrary code execution was achievable on host medical instrumentation. Validated and remediated via coordinated disclosure through Philips Product Security, resulting in a public Philips Hall of Honors induction (2026) in lieu of a standard CVE assignment.<br>
<a href="https://www.philips.com/a-w/security/coordinated-vulnerability-disclosure/hall-of-honors.html">Philips Hall of Honors</a>
</div>

<div class="card">
Oracle Security Issue (Critical Customer Data Information Disclosure)<br>
Critical information disclosure vulnerability affecting Oracle web infrastructure that exposed the user data of over 70,000 users, including payment details, email addresses, credentials, physical addresses, and organization information. The issue was resolved via total endpoint elimination through Oracle’s coordinated security disclosure program.<br>
<a href="https://www.oracle.com/security-alerts/cpujul2024.html">Oracle CPU Advisory</a>
</div>

<div class="card">
Conference Research: Prototype Pollution and ReDoS<br>
Research presentation covering prototype pollution exploitation patterns in JavaScript applications and regular expression denial-of-service conditions in real-world web systems.<br>
<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/posts/cybersherlock_cybersecurity-nullmeetmumbai-itminstitute-activity-7195110088628416512-Cg-U">Conference Post</a>
</div>

<div class="card">
Nullcon Goa 2023 Scholarship<br>
Selected scholarship recipient at Nullcon Goa 2023 for security research contributions and participation in offensive security and systems research discussions.<br>
<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/posts/nullcon_nullcongoa2023-infosec-conference-activity-7102622075843993600-64dZ">Nullcon Post</a>
</div>

<div class="card">
